  "description": "<section id=\"description\">\n<p>You are given a pizza (perfect circle) that has been cut into $m·n$ equal pieces and you want to have exactly one topping on each slice.</p>\n<p>Let $f(m,n)$ denote the number of ways you can have toppings on the pizza with $m$ different toppings ($m ≥ 2$), using each topping on exactly $n$ slices ($n ≥ 1$). Reflections are considered distinct, rotations are not.</p>\n<p>Thus, for instance, $f(2,1) = 1$, $f(2,2) = f(3,1) = 2$ and $f(3,2) = 16$. $f(3,2)$ is shown below:</p>\n<img class=\"img-responsive center-block\" alt=\"animation with 16 ways to have 3 different toppings on 2 slices each\" src=\"https://cdn.freecodecamp.org/curriculum/project-euler/pizza-toppings.gif\" style=\"background-color: white; padding: 10px;\">\n<p>Find the sum of all $f(m,n)$ such that $f(m,n) ≤ {10}^{15}$.</p>\n</section>",
